Kusama Auctions 6-11: Report (WIP)

Jonas Gehrlein

12/10/2021

Auction Schedule

The second batch of auctions was enabled by the governance body of the Kusama network and it was initially planned to allocate another set of five parachain slots. Later and after some discussion within the community, the council, as representatives of the token holders, schedule a sixth auction. This brings the total number of parachains as the time of writing to twelve (eleven allocated by auctions and Statemine as public good chain by governance). This was possible because experts agreed on the technical stability of the network and that the additional auction would fit the duration of the current crowdloans. In total, the whole campaign went on from September 01st until October 13th. Each auction lasted seven days with a two-day starting and five-day candle phase. The following table provides the dates for the four important events of each auction (the same table with the events expressed in their block heights can be found in the Appendix).

Preliminary notes

This is the second report on the Kusama parachain auctions and uses a similar layout as the first report. Detailed explanations about the candle mechanism applied in the auctions and the crowdloans are left out here, because they were already discussed in the first report. For readers unfamiliar with those concepts, the previous report can be found here [LINK].

Overview

In total, 16 crowdloans have registered to participate in the second batch of auctions and have received contributions during the campaign from 37208 unique accounts (49,749 accross both campaigns). A total number of 1,348,231 KSM was bonded to crowdloans. Hereof, 1,251,134 KSM has been locked in slots until August 05th, 2022, while the rest can be reclaimed by users, as their chosen crowdloans could not secure a parachain slot. At the time of the events, from all issued tokens, 44% are locked in staking and 20% are locked for crowdloans from auctions 1 - 11. Individual accounts selected on average to 2.2 crowdloans with an average of 36.23497 KSM per contribution.

The following table summarizes relevant metrics for the seven projects with the highest locked KSM for crowdloans ordered by the amount of contributions (the full table is available in the Appendix)).

The following graph shows the cumulative contributions of the seven highest-backed crowdloans for the whole campaign. This gives some visual insights about the contribution dynamic to the different projects.

We can spot a clear hierarchy between the contribution levels in the first three auctions, while things get more dynamic especially for the fourth auction. As all bids were made for the same leasing periods (full duration of the slot), contributions can be compared within a single graph. Upon visual inspection of the graph below, we can see that the contribution curve flattens out for several teams. There are two reasons for this. First, after a crowdloan won an auction, no more contributions are accepted by the Relay Chain. Second, once a crowdloan reaches it’s cap, contributions for that crowdloan are also not accepted anymore. During the whole campaign, six teams obtained a slot while three of them reached their crowdloan cap before their respective auction ended.

We’ll have a closer look at each auction in the following.

Auction 6-8

Similarly to the first batch of auctions, we observed three strong teams taking the lead from early on. Those managed to win auction 6-8 without much interference with each other. That means, at no point during the auctions, a winning bid has changed between a team. KILT Spiritnet, the winner of auction 6, reached their cap of 220’000 KSM shortly after the beginning of the first auction (and well before the candle period started) and won the first auction of the second batch. While the contribution levels of the two other teams came close to each other, the second auction was won by Calamari with a total of 218,248 locked KSM. Auction 8 was won by Basilisk after hitting their cap with a total of 222,222.

Auction 9

In auction 9, there were three teams that realistically had a chance to compete for the slot. Those were Altair, Parallel Heiko and Kintsugi BTC. While Altair could sustain their lead for quite a while, Parallel Heiko’s crowdloan exceeded the number of locked tokens during the candle period and consequently obtained the winning bid. While Kintsugi BTC’s crowdloan managed to secure a significant number of locked tokens in a short time, they surpassed Altair eventually, but were beaten by Parallel Heiko. The graph below illustrates the bidding over time.

We can see that Altair led the cumulative sum of contributions in the pre-candle phase and some time at the beginning of the decisive candle period. Specifically, they led around 35.2% of the candle phase. Eventually, in block number 9387388, Parallel Heiko’s crowdloan received a single contribution of 57,320 KSM which lead to their crowdloan getting ahead in the auction and securing the winning bid. Eventually, Kintsugi BTC also managed to overtake Altair, putting them in the last place for the ninth auction. Yet, Altair took back the lead over Kintsugi BTC shortly before the end of the auction to realize the second place. At the end of the auction, contributors bonded 187,836.2 KSM for Altair, 196,984.2 KSM for Parallel Heiko and 173,315.3 KSM for Kintsugi BTC. Technically, either Altair or Parallel Heiko could win this close race. Kintsugi BTC was not eligble for a win in this auction, because they never obtained a winning bid in the candle period. In the following graph, we increase the resolution to aggregated contributions on a block-level.

One vertical line indicates the block that was randomly chosen at the end of the auction and that the blockchain implemented the given winning bids in that block. On a closer look, the auction terminated shortly before Parallel Heiko could secure the lead, which eventually led that Altair won the ninth auction and obtained the respective slot.

Who blows out the candle? (CHECK TECHNICAL DETAILS)

At the end of the auction, Altair had the second-lowest amount of contributions of the three teams (and occasionally even the lowest). Yet, they have been chosen as the winner of the slot. How did that come about? The reason is that the figurative candle went out during the beginning of the candle period (at ~35% of the candle period) when Altair still was in the lead. As this happens retrospectively, we only learned about this after the auction ended. But who eventually blows out the candle?

To answer this question, we need to learn some more details about a technique that is applied: sampling. The candle period lasts exactly 72’000 blocks and is divided into 3600 samples (i.e., every 20 blocks). Those samples are essentially like any other block, but they also store the current winner(s) of the auction. Compared to the case of storing the information in all blocks, this vastly reduces storage requirements and thereby puts much less load on the blockchain. After the auction concludes, one of those samples is selected with equal probability. Then, the bidders that held the winning bid(s) at this selected block, are chosen to occupy the slot. As all samples have an equal probability to be selected and there are a sufficient number of samples, auctions should end, on average, at 50% of their candle period (later more on this).

But that does not yet answer who blows out the candle. To understand this, we need to familiarize ourselves with the concept of Verified Random Functions (VRF-LINK). Those functions, on a high level, provide provable randomness, i.e., it can be cryptographically shown that the result cannot be predicted before it actually appears. Not even by the entity that calculates the result. This is already an important feature in Polkadot’s (and hence Kusama’s) block production protocol BABE (LINK), which uses this to determine which validator may earn the right for producing blocks. Technically, the function takes a private key specific to each validator and the results of previous VRFs (public randomness) as input. If validators obtain a number smaller than some threshold as output of the function, they are eligible to produce a block in that slot. The inclusion of public randomness is a crucial part to prevent that results can be biased (e.g., by pre-computing). Most importantly, due to those properties, it can be mathematically proven that the result is random, cannot be tampered with, and that other nodes in the network can verify the result.

In the case of the candle auction, validators use the VRF to compute the random sample, containing the actual winner(s) of the auction and publishes it alongside a proof that makes the result verifiable. This happened in Block 9434278 at event with index 0 (LINK https://kusama.subscan.io/extrinsic/9434278-0?event=9434278-0) which is the WinningOffset. The number, in this case 1078, marks the sample that has been chosen as termination block of the respective auction. If we take the start block of the candle period, 9362014, and add 1078 * 20 = 21560 Blocks to it, we calculate the termination block, 9383574, ourselves. In conclusion, we can say that, technically, the validator that produces the block with the winning offset figuratively blows out the candle. Yet, it is important to note, that the respective validators don’t have any influence on the outcome.

-> How much can we verify without a node? -> Can we for example see the winning bids in the block? -> How is it determined when the winning offset is produced? Is it again some thresholds ?

Auction 10-11: Expected Chaos

Continuing with the lead from Auction 9, Parallel Heiko entered the bidding. With a strong position from the fourth auction, Parallel Heiko continued to compete for the it seemed, last available slot. The vertical line indicates the beginning of the candle phase.

While Parallel Heiko set a funding cap of 400’000 KSM and Kintsugi BTC of 200’000 KSM, the former was able to outcompete the latter. Because Parallel Heiko had the winning bid in 100% of the samples, it was clear that they would win the slot. After some discussions in the Kusama Direction Channel (LINK) and some assessments by experts about the stability of the network, the council scheduled an eleventh auction. This illustrates the flexibility of the Kusama governance body and the ability to quickly respond to new circumstances. In the absence of any competitors and as the crowdloan was already capped, Kintsugi BTC held the winning bid during the whole auction and thereby won the final slot of this batch.

The Impact of the Candle Mechanism

The candle auction is composed of two different stages, namely the starting and candle phase. The latter is further divided (retrospectively), into a period that falls before and after the termination block. This mechanism could lead to the situation that the highest bidder at the end of the auction does not necessarily win the auction, because their winning bid is discarded if it falls into the range after the termination block. This occurred during Auction 9. All tokens that are contributed to a winning crowdloan during the whole auction would still be locked for the entirety of the respective leasing period. This means that we could observe some inefficiency, both in determining the winner and in locking tokens that did not contribute to a higher winning bid. Summary

The second batch of auctions on Kusama has been concluded and all parachains have been successfully onboarded. The winners of this batch of auctions, in order, are KILT Spiritnet, Calamari, Basilisk, Altair, Parallel Heiko, and Kintsugi BTC. In this batch of auctions, there are three things to highlight.

First, we saw for the first time ever on any Kusama auction, that the candle mechanism picked a winner that was not in the lead at the end of the auction. This further emphasizes the importance of contributing as early as possible during the candle period, both for users as well as teams that might help their own crowdloan.

First, the crowdloan cap played a prominent role in the contribution and bidding dynamics. In fact, half of the teams reached their crowdloan cap. In the case of KILT Spiritnet, the crowdloan was already filled well before the decisive candle period started. This could serve as an important lesson for users to unbond their tokens early and schedule the unbonding time not directly to the start of the candle period, but, to be safe, well before that. While the cap mechanism did not lead to a different outcome of auctions, teams certainly have learned that it is an important parameter of their whole strategy. One reason for setting a cap is to control the maximum number of contributions, such that a fixed rate at which crowdloans gift their own tokens to supporters can be determined (at least the ‘worst’ rate). However, as we saw, the cap might become a parameter that decides about success or failure of a crowdloan. Teams might find themselves in a dilemma, where they want to start their crowdloan as soon as possible to catch the attention of supporters. However, this makes it possible for other teams to slightly outbid them on their cap, making it more likely to win in a close auction. This might have already happened as Basilisk set their cap to 222’000 KSM in response to KILT Spiritnet and their 220’000 KSM. In a close auction between the two teams, reaching the cap could have resulted in losing for KILT Spiritnet. It will be interesting to see how this dilemma plays out and how teams handle it in the future.

Third, we saw the governance body of Kusama react quickly and flexibly to new circumstances enabling another auction. This was possible, because of active discussions in the community and technical experts evaluating the stability of the network.
